{"author":"RebarBotNava","data":{"fields":{"description":"Activity-based liveness for LLM gate ops using mechanisms compatible with the runner's synchronous `agent.run_sync()`: a generous per-request READ timeout + a per-TOOL timeout, layered on the step caps the runner ALREADY derives. NO total-runtime timeout. The stream-event idle-watchdog is DEFERRED (it needs an async runner) — captured as ADR content for the integrator to record, NOT built here.\n\n## Why\nA single hard total-runtime timeout truncates healthy multi-minute / large-context (1M-token) runs; liveness must be gauged by activity, not total elapsed time. BUT the runner uses `agent.run_sync()` exclusively (a blocking synchronous call with no concurrent stream-event hooks). The LangGraph `idle_timeout` / Claude-SDK stall-watchdog pattern requires async `agent.run()` / `run_stream_events` + an event loop, which this runner does not have. So the correct in-architecture design achieves activity-based liveness at request+tool granularity WITHOUT asyncio.\n\n## What\n- **Per-request read timeout (both modes):** an `httpx.Timeout(read=cfg.timeout_s, connect=10.0, write=..., pool=...)` set on the shared `httpx.AsyncClient` that story arcticduck constructs (verified in-branch: `_build_retrying_anthropic_model(..., http_timeout=<httpx.Timeout>)` exists in `runner.py`, committed by arcticduck — review this story with `--ref` at the stack HEAD, not origin/main). NOTE: the read timeout REUSES the EXISTING `cfg.timeout_s` (600) — it is already the per-request timeout budget (today wired only to `model_settings['timeout']`); this story does NOT add a duplicate `llm_request_timeout_s` key. Setting it as the transport `read` gives a FINER, transport-level per-request bound at the same value. Sized ABOVE worst-case large-context prefill (a too-tight read timeout is the truncation bug in miniature); bounds a HUNG MODEL without a total-runtime cap. This wiring is Anthropic-path-only (OpenAI/Google build their own internal httpx clients — acceptable: the gates run on Anthropic; a follow-on can generalize).\n- **Per-tool timeout (agentic):** `Agent(tool_timeout=cfg.llm_tool_timeout_s)` bounds a hung TOOL. Added to the agentic `Agent(...)` construction kwargs.\n- **Step caps: ALREADY PRESENT — reused, not re-added.** The runner already derives `request_limit = max(1, ceil(max_iterations/2))` and `tool_calls_limit = max(8, max_iterations)` from `cfg.max_iterations` and applies them via `UsageLimits` on `run_sync` (pinned by story arawana's RED matrix). Those DERIVED caps ARE the infinite/oscillating-loop bound; this story does NOT add duplicate `request_limit`/`tool_calls_limit` config knobs (they would duplicate `cfg.max_iterations`). Single-turn/structured keeps its existing tighter `request_limit` (single call, no tool loop). So between \"hung request\" (read timeout), \"hung tool\" (tool timeout), and \"runaway loop\" (existing derived step caps), a healthy long run is never truncated and a stalled run is always caught — no total-runtime timeout, no event loop.\n- **Relationship to the existing `model_settings['timeout']`:** the runner already sets `model_settings['timeout'] = float(cfg.timeout_s)` (the SDK-level coarse per-request timeout). This story's `httpx.Timeout(read=...)` is the FINER transport-level per-attempt read bound and is the authoritative \"hung model\" signal; both coexist as layered bounds (SDK request timeout ⊇ transport read timeout). This story does NOT remove `model_settings['timeout']`; the two are consistent (both defaulting from generous values) and their reconciliation is noted for the integrator.\n- **Deferred (ADR content only, NOT built):** the sub-event stream-idle-watchdog (reset-on-stream-event) needs the async `agent.run()` / `run_stream_events` migration, conflicting with the exclusive `run_sync` design. This story PROVIDES the decision + async-migration-trigger CONTENT; the integrator story authorial-hated-blackbear RECORDS the ADR (sole ADR owner). A `discovered_from` follow-on ticket captures the migration trigger. (If ever built, wrap the event iterator to avoid pydantic-ai #4796.)\n\n## Verification (a probe that actually crosses the timeout layer)\nA `FunctionModel` is an in-process test double that never makes an HTTP request, so it CANNOT exercise an `httpx` read timeout. This story's probe therefore uses a **MockTransport whose handler sleeps** (the same seam story arcticduck's spike uses): with `httpx.Timeout(read=<small>)`, the sleeping handler trips `httpx.ReadTimeout` UNDER `agent.run_sync()`, proving the read timeout fires in the synchronous runner. The resulting `httpx.ReadTimeout` propagates to the runner's generic `except` seam, which raises `LLMUnavailableError` carrying an `.outcome` of `WAIT_AND_RETRY` (the classifier added by story mamba, already committed in `failure.py`). The HEALTHY-long-run case is proven by a MockTransport that responds JUST UNDER the read timeout and asserts the call completes normally (not aborted). The per-tool timeout is proven with a real `Agent` carrying a deliberately-sleeping tool and `tool_timeout=<small>`, asserting it trips. (Step caps are already proven by arawana's derived-limits test.)\n\n## Scope\n- ONE new `LLMConfig` key (NOT VerifyConfig — every LLM runtime knob lives on `LLMConfig` with a `REBAR_LLM_*` env, per arcticduck's precedent): `llm_tool_timeout_s` (default 120), read via `_llm_int` from `[llm]` + `REBAR_LLM_TOOL_TIMEOUT_S`. The per-request READ timeout reuses the existing `cfg.timeout_s` (no new key — avoids duplicating it). Regenerate `docs/env-vars.md`; add `REBAR_LLM_TOOL_TIMEOUT_S` to `test_config_llm.py`'s `_clean` fixture; document in `docs/config.md`.\n- Wire the `httpx.Timeout` into arcticduck's `_build_retrying_anthropic_model` call (build the object in `run()` from the two configs and pass `http_timeout=`), and add `tool_timeout=` to the agentic `Agent(...)` construction.\n- NOT in scope: any total-runtime cap (rejected — truncates healthy runs); the async stream-event watchdog (deferred, ADR content only); new step-cap config knobs (the derived caps already exist).\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] `LLMConfig.llm_tool_timeout_s` (120) exists, read from `[llm]` + `REBAR_LLM_TOOL_TIMEOUT_S`; the per-request read timeout reuses `cfg.timeout_s` (no duplicate key). `docs/env-vars.md` regenerated (CI drift gate passes) and `REBAR_LLM_TOOL_TIMEOUT_S` added to `test_config_llm.py`'s `_clean` fixture.\n- [ ] The per-request `httpx.Timeout(read=...)` is passed into arcticduck's `_build_retrying_anthropic_model(http_timeout=...)` for both modes; a MockTransport whose handler sleeps past the read timeout trips `httpx.ReadTimeout` under `run_sync` and surfaces as a classified failure (probe test).\n- [ ] The agentic `Agent(...)` sets `tool_timeout=cfg.llm_tool_timeout_s`; a deliberately-sleeping tool trips it (probe test). A slow-but-live model returning JUST under the read timeout is NOT aborted (healthy-long-run test).\n- [ ] No total-runtime timeout exists in the gate path and no asyncio/event loop is introduced (asserted); the existing derived step caps (arawana) are unchanged.\n- [ ] This story provides the deferred-async-watchdog ADR CONTENT (recorded by blackbear) and files a `discovered_from` follow-on for the async-migration trigger.\n- [ ] `make test`/`make lint`/`make typecheck` green.\n\nFiles: `src/rebar/llm/runner.py` (build+pass `httpx.Timeout` via arcticduck's `http_timeout` seam; add `tool_timeout` to the agentic Agent), `src/rebar/llm/config.py` (two LLMConfig keys + `from_env`), `docs/config.md`, `docs/env-vars.md` (regenerated), `tests/unit/test_config_llm.py` (`_clean` fixture), `docs/adr/00XX-async-liveness-watchdog.md` (content, numbered by blackbear), `tests/unit/test_llm_timeouts.py` (new — read-timeout + tool-timeout probes + no-total-runtime-cap assertion). The deferred-watchdog ADR content is authored here at `docs/adr/00XX-async-liveness-watchdog.md` (a placeholder number blackbear assigns/records as the sole ADR owner, with Context/Decision/Consequences on why the stream-event watchdog is deferred pending the async-runner migration).\n\n## Verified library behavior (experiment log — pydantic-ai 1.107.0, httpx 0.28.1, offline)\nACTUAL captured output (no billable call):\n```\nAgent.__init__ has tool_timeout:            True   (per-tool execution timeout hook exists)\nAgent.run_sync has usage_limits:            True   (step caps go on run*, not the constructor)\nhttpx.Timeout(600.0, read=300.0, connect=10.0).read == 300.0   (per-request read timeout is settable)\nUsageLimits fields: [request_limit, tool_calls_limit, input_tokens_limit, output_tokens_limit,\n                     total_tokens_limit, count_tokens_before_request, ...]   (total_tokens_limit exists)\n```\nSo the run_sync-compatible liveness mechanisms this story wires — httpx.Timeout(read=) on the shared\nclient (owned by story arcticduck), Agent(tool_timeout=), and UsageLimits step caps incl.\ntotal_tokens_limit on run_sync — are all real 1.107.0 API. No asyncio / stream-event watchdog is\nintroduced (that path needs async agent.run(); DEFERRED per ADR). These are pydantic-ai/httpx LIBRARY\nsymbols, not rebar symbols (bug succinct-formable-kite: repo-absence != non-existence)."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1783655326895494001,"uuid":"640d1e16-ebc4-4322-b98d-f39c834a33e8"}